context: While exploring inland along the <a0_0>northern coast of Florida<a0_0/> in <a1_0>1528<a1_0/>, the members of <b6_0>the Narváez expedition<b6_0/>, including <b7_0>Álvar Núñez Cabeza de Vaca<b7_0/>, found a Native American village near present-day Tallahassee, Florida whose name they transcribed as <a2_0><b8_0>Apalchen<a2_0/> or Apalachen<b8_0/> [a.paˈla.tʃɛn]. The name was soon altered by the Spanish to Apalachee and used <a3_0>as a name for the tribe and region spreading well inland to the north<a3_0/>. Pánfilo de Narváez's expedition first entered Apalachee territory on <b4_0>June 15, 1528<b4_0/>, and applied the name. Now spelled "<b5_0>Appalachian<b5_0/>," it is the fourth-oldest surviving European place-name in the US.
